column15: As published on the NSW Health Government website on the 12th of August 2021, stay at home orders including school cosures for additional Local Government Areas (LGA) were in place from 5pm 12th of August 2021. The policy was implemented for additional LGAs (Bayside, Burwood, and Strathfield), and was already in place for Blacktown, Campbelltown, Canterbury-Bankstown, Cumberland, Fairfield, Georges River, Liverpool, Parramatta, and 12 suburbs in the Penrith LGA.    This represents a tightening of the policy response to COVID-19, as more areas in the region were affected.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111051024/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20210812_00.aspx

C1: Schools in the Northern Territory were open during this period of time. Student attendance in-person returned to close to normal in May of 2020 and schools were functioning as normal from June 2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210128055448/https://education.nt.gov.au/publications/information-for-term-4-2020
column24: Businesses are essentially open as normal with some minor compliance around COVID safety planning and have been since mid-2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210118172628/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business#/events_and_gatherings
column33: Public events have additional COVID-safety guidelines however are functioning as normal with no density or percentage capacity restrictions.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210111054507/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/more_than_500_people
column42: Gatherings over 100 have extra guidelines (specifically a COVID-safe checklist), gatherings over 500 people require the approval of state government. These guidelines have been in place since at least September 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210111054507/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/more_than_500_people
column51: There is no evidence that public transport was ever restricted during the pandemic.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210205151150/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/public-transport
column60: The Northern Territory was not under any stay-at-home orders or guidance during this period. In fact the Northern Territory never had a stay-at-home policy in place during the pandemic.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210118172628/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business#/events_and_gatherings
column69: The territory restricts entry from areas declared hotspots. From 1 January to 1 February, there was restriction on travel from LGAs in NSW.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210424124155/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/quarantine/hotspots-covid-19/former-declared-hotspots
column79: The Northern Territory Government was the only Australian government to not implement a moratorium on evictions during the pandemic after other jurisdictions agreed to this measure in National Cabinet in April. The Northern Territory made some minor changes around notices to tenants and encouraged landlords and tenants to negotiate relief voluntarily. There was also no policy around relief for mortgages (though Australian governments did lobby banks to provide voluntary mortgage relief early in the pandemic which could have benefitted many Territorians)  https://web.archive.org/web/20210419092157/https://consumeraffairs.nt.gov.au/rental-changes-due-to-covid-19  The government did create a program for debt and contract relief for small and medium-sized businesses effective from at least October 21 2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210314235933/https://business.gov.au/grants-and-programs/Business-Hardship-Package-NT
column86: The Territory has had a coordinated campaign since February 2020. This includes a COVID website and regular updates from the Chief Minister and other officials.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210120003338/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/
column88: Throughout the pandemic, anyone in the Northern Territory with COVID symptoms could access a COVID test.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201231020114/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/symptoms-testing
column90: The Northern Territory has never had a locally acquired COVID case so it is very difficult to know how good its contact tracing system is. The Territory has implemented contact tracing standards in line with much of Australia since November 2020 including a check-in app released by government which is mandatory in public venues.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210308031847/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/safety-supervisors-and-contact-tracing
column103: Face coverings were not mandated anywhere in the NT from 16 - 19 January 2021.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210511022551if_/https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/nt-moves-on-masks-in-airports-and-planes-c-1986183
column106: Vaccinations had not yet begun in the Territory. The first vaccinations in Australia happened on February 22nd 2021.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210508062151/https://www.health.gov.au/news/first-covid-19-vaccinations-in-australia
column115: Anyone with COVID symptoms or who was a close contact of a case could not visit residential aged-care. This was the case since at least 29 July 2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210427071803/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/advice-care/residential-aged-care

column103: After a decision by National Cabinet, masks became mandatory in all Australian airports. This entered effect in the NT under a state government directive on January 20 2020 after masks had previously not been needed anywhere in the state.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210511022551if_/https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/nt-moves-on-masks-in-airports-and-planes-c-1986183

column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, no foreign arrivals are permitted into the country unless they are in an exempt category or have been granted an individual exemption which includes compassionate and national interest grounds. All international arrivals must quarantine for 14 days at a designated facility. There is the possibility to travel to Australia quarantine free without an exemption if you have been in New Zealand for 14 days or more and not been in a designated COVID-19 outbreak location, and you are travelling to Australia on a quarantine-free flight from 14/12/2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210101130014/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions   https://web.archive.org/web/20201231084847/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/new-zealand-safe-travel-zone
column77: Individuals are able to receive a $150 coronavirus supplement per fortnight from 01/01/2021 to 31/03/2021 which represents $100 less than the policy previous ending on 31/12/2020. Individuals can receive a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment of $1400 for each 14 day period someone self-isolate, quarantine or care for a person who has COVID-19 through Centrelink as published on the Services Australia website last updated on 12/12/2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201222113322/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/coronavirus-supplement   https://web.archive.org/web/20210305094501mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment

column15: The archived link below provided for Queensland school policy effective on 17 November 2020. This policy is not a targeted policy and applies to the whole state.   https://web.archive.org/web/20201130014209/https://qed.qld.gov.au/about-us/news-and-media/novel-coronavirus/covid-19-operating-guidelines-for-queensland-state-schools#school-functions
column69: People from certain hotspots require Border Pass to enter Queensland. For example, the archived link below shows that from 22 December 2020, people from New South Wales need the Border Pass to enter the Queensland area and Queensland Police will meet all arrivals to enforce the rules.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210111055333/https://www.qld.gov.au/border-pass

column15: Greater Brisbane is in lockdown from 5pm 29 March to 5pm 1 April 2021. Schools have closed from Tuesday 30 March in an early end to Term 1.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210426194844/https://www.covid19.qld.gov.au/help-and-advice/education

The lockdown restrictions in Greater Brisbane were lifted from midday of 01/April.2021,  https://www.health.gov.au/news/announcements/protecting-older-australians-covid-19-update-1-april-2021(This link can't be archived)

column86: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 12th December 2021, Tasmanian Government through The Business Tasmania team, alongside Public Health and WorkSafe, supports businesses to have all information and confidence needed for border reopening 15 December 2021. There have been series of face-to face sector-specific forums and comprehensive online videos to address any questions. Videos are on the Business Tasmania website. Roger Jaensch, Minister for State Growth.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220101213558/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/supporting-businesses-for-the-reopening-of-our-border

As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 13th December 2021, the Public Health Hotline has proven essential and has therefore been increased currently employing more than 100 Tasmanians to support the community with information and assist with vaccination or testing bookings.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220101220013/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/public-health-hotline-local-and-ready-to-help
column88: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 10/12/2021, the state is increasing testing capacity across all regions to approximately 5,000 in partnerships with the North West Pathology, Launceston Pathology, and Hobart Pathology to operate clinics in Burnie, Launceston, and Hobart respectively from Monday 13 December 2021. These clinics will be drive-through, have no requirement to book in advance, free of charge and most convenient for people wishing to get tested as part of domestic travel requirements from December 15, 2021. This represents an increase in testing capacity of the policy response to COVID-19 as the state government continues to maintain regional testing capacity with the cooperation of district hospitals and health center sites, whilst seeking further increase in testing capacity. Jeremy Rockliff, Minister for Health.        http://web.archive.org/web/20220101000841/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/increase-in-testing-capacity

column69: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 15th December 2021, additional local government areas (LGAs) in New South Wales and Victoria have been declared high-risk. Anyone travelling from a high-risk area must have a Tas e-Travel pass and negative COVID-19 test before arrival.      http://web.archive.org/web/20220103070330/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/lgas-in-victoria-and-nsw-declared-high-risk
column88: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 15th December 2021, anyone currently in Tasmania who has been in any of the high risk areas declared, must self monitor for symptoms, even if very mild and get tested immediately.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220103070330/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/lgas-in-victoria-and-nsw-declared-high-risk
column103: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, last updated 24th December, masks are mandatory in all public indoor spaces for people aged 12 years and older (unless exempt) in Tasmania.  These are identified as workplaces, educational settings (excluding primary school children but including staff), businesses, shops & accommodation, boats, indoor sporting & exercise facilities, service providers like banks, churches, centrelink, public transport, airports, aircrafts and outdoor events.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220111085651/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public

column86: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 18th December 2021, more COVID-19 exposure sites have been identified and regularly updated at coronavirus.tas.gov.au for the general public awareness.  The Department of Health will report daily, all COVID-19 case numbers, testing numbers and vaccination progress, posted on the Departments Facebook page.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220103070610/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/additional-covid-19-exposure-sites
column88: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 18th December 2021, anyone in Norwood, Launceston area experiencing any COVID-19 symptoms, regardless of how mild, should get tested immediately.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220103070238/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/covid-19-case-detected-in-northern-tasmania

column90: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website on 22nd December 2021, by 8pm Public Health Services had identified 12 cases of COVID-19 in Tasmania and is conducting contact tracing for all cases.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220105100355/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/covid-19-case-update2

column88: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 23rd December 2021, clinically recommended external triage areas are being prepared as a contingency for additional patient screening in the event Tasmania experiences community transmission of COVID-19.      http://web.archive.org/web/20220105111911/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/external-triage-areas-tested-at-rhh

column90: As published at Tasmanian Government COVID-19 Website, Media release on 25th December 2021, The Royal Hobart Hospital Incident Management Team is prioritizing contacting and testing all staff and patients who may have been exposed to the positive case of an employee.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220118000424/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/media-releases/royal-hobart-hospital-employee-covid-19-case

column88: According to the information published on the Department of Health website on 16th October 2020, the national government policy for testing is that anyone with cold or flu-like symptoms should get tested. However, as the situation changes, states and territories may adjust their testing criteria based on local needs. This represents continuation in the COVID-19 policy response. This policy remained current on 17 January 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211127034515/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/ongoing-support-during-coronavirus-covid-19/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19

column86: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503095648if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/vaccine
column88: People should get tested if they have any symptoms, no matter how mild. Archived web: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503165307if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/taking-test-covid-19#who-should-get-tested
column90: Comprehensive contact tracing for all identified cases. Check-in everywhere people visit using the state governments Service Victoria QR codeapp, no matter how long a person spends at a location. Web archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503165307if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/coronavirus-covidsafe-settings
column103: You must always carry a face mask with you at all times when you leave the home, unless you have a lawful reason not to. Face masks are mandatory indoors unless an exception applies, or you are:  	at home  	at work, if a member of the public isnt present and you are in an area that members of the public cant normally access (such as an office space or a factory)  	a staff member at a school, childcare or early childhood service, and a member of the public isnt present (apart from at reception, where masks are always required)  	a student at school  Face masks are recommended outdoors where physical distancing of at least 1.5 metres cannot be maintained, for example, at a busy open-air market or a bus stop.  Web archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503165307if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/coronavirus-covidsafe-settings
column106: The vaccination program in Australia commenced in Victoria from 22 Feb 2021. According to the state government, the vaccine is safe, free and universal. The rollout of the vaccine is made available in phases, with certain groups at highest risk of infection getting the first doses. Currently people in phase 1a and phase 1b are eligible to receive COVID-19 vaccines. From 3 May people who are 50 years and older are eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine.  Web archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503095648if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/vaccine
column115: Visitors of any age may visit a care facility (including people aged under 16 years). Visitors can be from different households, and they can bring dependents if alternative care arrangement cannot be made. Face masks must be worn.   People cannot visit a care facility (unless they have an exemption) if they are unwell with any COVID-19-like symptoms, waiting a COVID-19 test result, have arrived in Australia within the last 14 days (unless from a green zone), under self-isolation waiting clearance, and have visited a Tier 1 exposure site and advised to isolate, get tested and isolated for 14 days.   Some care facilities may have further limit visits.  Web archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20210503165307if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/visiting-care-facilities and http://web.archive.org/web/20210503165307if_/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/coronavirus-covidsafe-settings

column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, no foreign arrivals are permitted into the country unless they are in an exempt category or have been granted an individual exemption which includes compassionate and national interest grounds. column77: Individuals are able to receive a $150 coronavirus supplement per fortnight from 01/01/2021 which represents $100 less than the policy previous ending on 31/12/2020. column103: As published on the Department of Health website, updated on 07/01/2021, there is no national requirement on face masks. column106: There are no vaccines available in Australia until 22/02/2022. The archived link below also shows Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on reducing COVID transmission in schools and that state and territory governments are operating schools to local circumstances.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210712060853/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-reducing-the-potential-risk-of-covid-19-transmission-in-schools  https://web.archive.org/web/20210712143003/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/resources/help-stop-spread-resource-teachers-and-school-staff
column24: As published on 04/01/2021 on the federal government's Business site all restrictions and measures will be implemented in accordance with state and territory laws for workplace closures. Indicating that workplace closure are enforced at a state and territory level on 12/02/2021, representing a continuation of the policy response of workplace closures at a national level.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210122171546/https://business.gov.au/risk-management/emergency-management/coronavirus-information-and-support-for-business/restrictions-on-non-essential-services
column33: As published on the Federal Governments Department of Healths website last updated on 26/06/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public events. There is no national policy on 12/02/2021 and this represents a continuation of the policy response. Archived link provides state and territory restrictions.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210105023903/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column42: As published on the Federal Governments Department of Healths website last updated on 26/06/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public gatherings. There is no national policy on 12/02/2021 and this represents a continuation of the policy response. Archived link provides state and territory restrictions.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210105023903/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column51: Public transport closures and requirements are under the responsibilities of local jurisdictions, however, the Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development and Communications released a document outlining the Principles for Covid-19 Public Transport Operations on 29/05/2020. This document provides advice for commuters and operators for COVID safe environment on public transport such as providing contactless facilities, reducing transport lengths and regular transport sanitisation. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210712064038/https://www.infrastructure.gov.au/transport/files/COVID19_public_transport_principles_29052020.pdf
column60: As published on the Federal Governments Department of Healths website last updated on 26/06/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public gatherings and the national government encourages social distancing and good hygiene practice whilst in public. This represents a continuation of the policy response with no national stay at home requirement.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210105023903/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column69: As updated on 26/06/2020 the Department of Health released the 3-step Framework for a COVIDSafe Australia which outlines that the public should refer to state and territory governments for border and internal movement restrictions. This policy is a continuation of the policy prior and in place on 12/02/2021.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210118144251/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/3-step-framework-for-a-covidsafe-australia
column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, no foreign arrivals are permitted into the country unless they are in an exempt category or have been granted an individual exemption which includes compassionate and national interest grounds. All international arrivals must quarantine for 14 days at a designated facility. There is the possibility to travel to Australia quarantine free without an exemption if you have been in New Zealand for 14 days or more and not been in a designated COVID-19 outbreak location, and you are travelling to Australia on a quarantine-free flight from 14/12/2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210211052018/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions   https://web.archive.org/web/20201231084847/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/new-zealand-safe-travel-zone
column77: Individuals are able to receive a $150 coronavirus supplement per fortnight from 01/01/2021 which represents a $100 less than the policy previous ending on 31/12/2020. Individuals can receive a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment of $1400 for each 14 day period someone self-isolate, quarantine or care for a person who has COVID-19 through Centrelink as published on the Services Australia website last updated on 12/12/2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210212070901/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/coronavirus-supplement  https://web.archive.org/web/20210305094501mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment
column79: Some state and territory governments may have some debt and contract relief under specific directions, but no national policy. However, the Australian Energy Regulator allows individuals to claim Covid hardship for a deferment of energy payment and other hardship support until 31/03/2021. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210203203703/https://www.energy.gov.au/covid-19-information/support-australian-households  https://web.archive.org/web/20210227002017/https://www.australia.gov.au/work-and-financial-support
column86: A range of public health campaigns remain in place across broad media platforms including the COVIDSafe campaign and other targeted campaigns. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210130222530/https://www.australia.gov.au/covidsafe-resources  https://web.archive.org/web/20210218235206/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-resources
column88: The national guideline for testing is that anyone with cold or flu-like symptoms should get tested, however,  as the situation changes, states and territories may adjust their testing criteria based on local needs. As published on the Australian governments Department of Healths website on 16/10/2020 and currently in place. This policy represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210212181442/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19
column90: There is no national contact tracing in place and is delegated to state and territory jurisdictions, although, the national government released a voluntary COVIDSafe app that uses Bluetooth to track contacts, but debates surround its effectiveness. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210127215946/https://covidsafe.gov.au/
column103: As published on the Department of Health website, updated on 07/01/2021, there is no national requirement on face masks, however, where there is significant community transmission (as determined by jurisdictional public health authorities), you may choose, or be required to, wear a mask. If physical distance is difficult to maintain, for example on public transport, covering your face with a mask can provide some extra protection. Face masks requirements are imposed at state and territory levels which can be found in archived link.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223005109/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/masks
column106: There are no vaccines available in Australia until 22/02/2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201211011613/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/about-covid-19-vaccines
column115: As published on the Department of Healths website aged care visitation and covid restrictions are outlined at state and territory jurisdictions and may vary depending on case numbers. There are recommendations for aged care facility protections as such in the National COVID-19 aged care plan. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210215191906/https://www.health.gov.au/health-topics/aged-care/advice-on-aged-care-during-covid-19.advice-for-the-aged-care-sector

column106: From March 22, the COVID-19 vaccine national rollout strategy has entered phase 1b.  Phase 1a included quarantine and border workers, health workers, aged care and disability care staff (aka "keyworkers", group 1) and residents (group 2). Phase 1b has included the elderly (70+), aboriginal and Torres-strait islander people and individuals with specific health conditions to be vaccinated. The vaccine is government-funded. Phase 1b includes 4 groups, an increase of 2 groups after phase 1a. According to the interpretation guide, a code of "4" means "availability for all three plus partial additional availability".  https://web.archive.org/web/20210712090928/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2021/03/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-update-on-22-march-2021.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20210401095153if_/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-vaccinated-for-covid-19/how-will-i-get-my-covid-19-vaccine

column74: Australian borders remain closed.  According to The Australian government, the only exceptions are "Australian citizens, permanent residents, immediate family members, and travellers who have been in New Zealand for at least the 14 days before the date of departure. This does not include the Realm Countries of the Cook Islands and Niue."    Quarantine free travel continues between Australia and New Zealand.    From 15 May, some repatriation flights from India to Australia restarted, but individuals only allowed on these flights dependent on certain exemptions from Home Affairs. These include compassionate reasons, critical workers, escorting minors, and those working in the national interest.     https://web.archive.org/web/20210806142559/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-restrictions/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-international-travellers    https://web.archive.org/web/20210806022138/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: For the period extending from 1 to 14 May, some forms of income supports are available. According to the Services Australia website (Last update 30 March 2021) "The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) is a one-off payment if youre affected by coronavirus (COVID-19). To get this you must be: eligible for an income support payment or ABSTUDY Living Allowance; in severe financial hardship; in Australia when you claim".    There is also a "Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment" for those who can't earn an income because they must self-isolate or quarantine themselves, or are caring for someone with COVID-19". column69: For the period between 1 July 2021 and 30 July 2021, there was no national policy regarding restrictions on internal movement. column74: As noted on the website of Department of Home Affairs, Australias borders are currently closed and travel to Australia is only available if you are exempt or you have been granted an individual exemption. All international arrivals must quarantine for 14 days upon arrival. The only exception is the quarantine free travel bubble with New Zealand which available on 18th April 2021. All travelers who have been in either Australia or New Zealand for 14 days can travel by air between Australia and New Zealand quarantine-free, without the need to apply for a travel exemption.  Archive link: https://web.archive.org/web/20210727033835/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20210727034118/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/new-zealand-safe-travel-zone
column77: Individuals may be eligible for various types of income support. There are three main types. The 'COVID-19 Disaster Payment' is a lump sum payment to help workers unable to earn income due to a COVID-19 state or territory public health order. This may involve a lockdown, hotspot or movement restrictions. The 'Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment' and the 'Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19)' provides income support for those who are required to enter quarantine or isolation.     This is a continuation of the national policy response to COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211004190443/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/subjects/getting-help-during-coronavirus-covid-19/if-you-need-payment
column79: There is no national policy on debt/ contract relief for households. This is a continuation of the national policy response to COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211004191635/https://www.aer.gov.au/publications/corporate-documents/statement-of-expectations-of-energy-businesses-protecting-customers-and-the-energy-market-during-covid-19

column88: The national policy for testing is that anyone with cold or flu-like symptoms should get tested. column103: As published on the Department of Health website, updated on 18/03/2021, there is no national requirement on face masks. column106: As stated on the website of Department of Health on 28 July 2021, COVID vaccines are eligible for people over the age of 40. column106: Between 1 August 2021 and 29 August 2021, both Oxford AstraZeneca and Pfizer vaccines were being administered. The availability and uptake of each brand for certain age groups depended on whether the sub-national jurisdiction was experiencing an outbreak (See ATAGI statement). Generally, the national vaccine rollout was at phase 2a, meaning that adults aged 40 or above and other persons from certain backgrounds, occupations or with certain medical conditions were able to receive the vaccine.     This is a continuation of phase 2a of the vaccine rollout that begun on 8 June 2021. Note that whilst the national vaccine rollout/ availability was at phase 2a, there were significant diversions of Pfizer vaccines to areas experiencing outbreaks for residents there beyond the phase 2a cohort.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211004201858/https://www.health.gov.au/news/covid-19-vaccines-to-be-available-to-everyone-aged-40-years-and-over  https://web.archive.org/web/20211004202146/https://www.health.gov.au/news/atagi-statement-on-use-of-covid-19-vaccines-in-an-outbreak-setting

According to the AHPPC on 26 July 2021, if there are Delta cases in the community a risk assessment will be undertaken by the jurisdiction that will consider the measures that need to be applied commensurate with the risk. AHPPC recognises the serious impact school closures have on all children and the need for the response to be proportionate to the risk of transmission in the school setting. During closures, vulnerable students and children of essential workers need to have continued access to onsite education. AHPPC continues to emphasise the importance of COVIDSafe plans and principles being embedded in school operations. When there are no local cases of COVID-19, standard plans include ensuring that; students and staff with symptoms do not attend school, visitors to the school are registered such as through QR codes. There needs to be importance placed on hand and respiratory hygiene along with good ventilation, regular cleaning and disinfection of the environment.    According to the Australian Government's webpage updated on 9 September 2021, the Corminaty (Pfizer) and Spikevax (Moderna) COVID-19 vaccines are approved and  recommended for people aged 12 and older. But it is not mandatory for students to get vaccinated. Therefore, it should be reported as 0. column77: The COVID-19 Disaster Payment is available to people who cannot attend work because they live or work in a Commonwealth-designated COVID-19 hotspot. The payment was $200 per week for those who are already receiving income support and lose at least 8 hours a week, $450 per week for those who lose 8-20 hours a week, and $750 per week for those who lose 20 or more hours per week. The $750 weekly payment week is more than half the median income, which is $1209 per week.(http://web.archive.org/web/20220121014642/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-work-hours).     The COVID-19 Disaster Payment automatic weekly payment will stop available when the states and territories reach 70% full vaccination for population aged 16 and above.     Apart from that, the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available for people who cannot work because they are required to isolate due to COVID-19, or are caring for someone who is required to isolate. The payment is $1500 for each 14-day isolation period, which is more than half the median fortnightly income of $2418. - The eligibility criteria for these payments make no mention of formal or informal employment, with all workers who lost significant income due to lockdowns or isolation requirements entitled to receive support.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220220083607/https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/rp2122/Quick_Guides/COVID-19DisasterPayments  https://web.archive.org/web/20211001040822/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/covid-19-disaster-payment

column88: The Australian Government recommends COVID-19 testing for "suspect cases": people who have COVID-19 symptoms and have, in the past 14 days: been in close contact with a confirmed case; been overseas, on a cruise ship, or to a COVID-19 hotspot in Australia; or have had direct patient contact in a health care or residential care setting. Also, people who do not qualify as "suspect cases" may also get tested if they have symptoms, live or work in a high-risk setting, are an organ donor or recipient, or are a returned traveler in quarantine.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201117175332/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/09/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-people-tested-for-covid-19_0.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20211002095837/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/ongoing-support-during-coronavirus-covid-19/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19#how-to-get-tested), despite the national testing policy, state and territory health authorities may modify testing criteria according to local needs.
column90: Each state or territory is responsible in contact tracing as most states or territory has developed their own app for venue check-ins. The Australian Government has developed the COVIDSafe app, which uses Bluetooth to detect potential contacts and assist state and territory health departments with manual contact tracing. However, the use of COVIDSafe app is voluntary. This represents the continuation of policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210626000319/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/apps-and-tools/covidsafe-app
column103: Face mask advice and mandates fall as the responsibility of local, state and territory governments. There is no nationwide mask policy. This is a continuation of policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211007112219/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/masks.
column106: According to Department of Health page which was updated on 25 Sept 2021, everyone aged 12 years and older is eligible for COVID-19 vaccination. Australia uses the AstraZeneca, Moderna, and Pfizer vaccines; Moderna and Pfizer are available for those aged between 12 and 59, while AstraZeneca is available for those aged 60 years and older, or anyone 18 years and older who choose to have it after discussing with their health professional. This is a continuation of previous policy as children aged between 12 and 15 years old became eligible to book COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine from September 13.     https://web.archive.org/web/20210926042215/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated
column115: Ultimate responsibility of managing COVID-19 risks among aged care facilities is placed on the state or territory governments. The Australian government Department of Health provides a national guidelines which outlines checklist to be prepared against COVID-19 outbreaks.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210403151253/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/collections/national-covid-19-aged-care-plan    https://web.archive.org/web/20211126155155/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2021/03/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia_0.pdf.

column15: As of 9 October 2021, the national government's Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advises that schools can safely open for students, but there is no compulsory national policy and final decisions on schools are made by state and territory governments (see https://web.archive.org/web/20211009210921/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19). This is a continuation of conditions in place since at least May 2020 (see older versions of archived link).
column24: According to the Australian Government's Business website, COVID-19 related restrictions on businesses are the responsibility of state and territory governments. See https://web.archive.org/web/20210929123134/https://business.gov.au/risk-management/emergency-management/coronavirus-information-and-support-for-business/business-restrictions-during-covid-19.
column33: As of 9 October 2021, restrictions on gatherings are set by state and territory governments, and there is no national policy on gatherings or public events. This has been the case since at least June 26, 2020. See the Department of Health's advice at https://web.archive.org/web/20211009210921/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19.
column42: As of 9 October 2021, restrictions on gatherings are set by state and territory governments, and there is no national policy on gatherings (see https://web.archive.org/web/20211009210921/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19). This has been the case since at least May 2020 (see older versions of archived link).
column51: There is no nationwide closure of public transport. The national government's guidance, summarised in the link below, is focused on keeping public transport operational in a Covid-safe way. Suggested measures include social distancing, hygiene and cleaning protocols, cashless payment of fares, and avoidance of public transport when experiencing Covid-19 symptoms. This is a continuation of policy in place since at least May 2020.    See https://web.archive.org/web/20210712064038/https://www.infrastructure.gov.au/transport/files/COVID19_public_transport_principles_29052020.pdf
column60: As of 7 October 2021, policies such as lockdowns, stay-at-home orders, and gathering restrictions were the responsibility of state and local governments. The federal government had no national-level stay-at-home policy. This is a continuation of conditions in place since at least May 2020. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211009210921/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column69: As noted on the Department of Health's website (see http://web.archive.org/web/20211010194330/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-restrictions/coronavirus-covid-19-domestic-travel-restrictions-and-remote-area-access), states and territories may impose restrictions on domestic travel, such as limiting travel in or out of the state, limiting travel between certain areas within the state, or imposing quarantine requirements. The national government designates COVID-19 "hot spots" for the purposes of financial support, but is not responsible for domestic travel restrictions.
column74: As of 7 October 2021, Australia's borders are closed except for those who have obtained an exemption. Certain categories of people are automatically exempt, including Australian citizens and permanent residents and their immediate family, New Zealand citizens who live in Australia, diplomats and their immediate family, people transiting through Australia for less than 72 hours, air and maritime crew, and holders of certain visas. People who are not included in these categories may request individual exemptions. While the Australian Government has plans to allow fully vaccinated citizens and permanent residents to travel internationally without an exemption, the current restrictions apply regardless of vaccination status.  See https://web.archive.org/web/20211007004301/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions.
column77: -	People who cannot work due to COVID-19 related reasons may be eligible to receive income support from the Australian Government.  -	The COVID-19 Disaster Payment is available to people who cannot attend work because they live or work in a Commonwealth-designated COVID-19 hotspot. The payment was $200 per week for those who are already receiving income support and lose at least 8 hours a week, $450 per week for those not already receiving income support and lose 8-20 hours a week, and $750 per week for those not already receiving income support who lose 20 or more hours per week. The maximum payment amount of $750 per week is more than half the median income, which is $1209 per week (http://web.archive.org/web/20220121014642/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-work-hours).   -	The Government began phasing out the COVID-19 Disaster Payment when states and territories reached 70% full vaccination rate among the 16+ population. At 70 percent vaccination rate, automatic renewal of payments would end, and at 80 percent the payments would be gradually withdrawn. As of 7 October 2021, only NSW and the ACT had reached the 70% threshold, and no jurisdictions had reached the 80% threshold.  -	The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available for people who cannot work because they are required to isolate due to COVID-19, or are caring for someone who is required to isolate. The payment is $1500 for each 14-day isolation period, which is more than half the median fortnightly income of $2418.  -	The eligibility criteria for these payments make no mention of formal or informal employment, with all workers who lost significant income due to lockdowns or isolation requirements entitled to receive support.  -	See http://web.archive.org/web/20220119223147/https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/rp2122/Quick_Guides/COVID-19DisasterPayments for information on these payments.
column79: -	The following document by the Australian Council of Social Services (ACOSS) notes that eviction moratoriums during 2020 and 2021 were implemented by state and territory governments, not the Australian government. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220221074745/https://www.acoss.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Covid-19_rental-housing-and-homelessness-impacts-in-Australia-v2.pdf.  -	The Australian Government provided a supplementary Rent Assistance payment during the period from September-December 2021 (see https://web.archive.org/web/20220221074949/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/co029-2109v3.pdf), but this payment was unrelated to COVID-19 and existed prior to the pandemic.  -	The Australian Energy Regulator stipulated in its Statement of Expectations (https://web.archive.org/web/20211004191635/https://www.aer.gov.au/publications/corporate-documents/statement-of-expectations-of-energy-businesses-protecting-customers-and-the-energy-market-during-covid-19) that energy companies should not shut off power to households and small businesses that are struggling to pay as a result of COVID-19.
column86: The Australian government runs a coordinated public information campaign about COVID-19. For example, the Department of Health website contains a range of COVID-19 related resources including statistics, latest updates, coronavirus symptoms, current rules and advice, and vaccination information. The Department of Health also runs the Coronavirus Australia news app and a WhatsApp channel. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211004112135/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/government-response-to-the-covid-19-outbreak.
column88: The Australian Government's guidance (see https://web.archive.org/web/20201117175332/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/09/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-people-tested-for-covid-19_0.pdf) recommends COVID-19 testing for "suspect cases": people who have COVID-19 symptoms and have, in the past 14 days: been in close contact with a confirmed case; been overseas, on a cruise ship, or to a COVID-19 hotspot in Australia; or have had direct patient contact in a health care or residential care setting. Under this guidance, people who do not qualify as "suspect cases" may also get tested if they have symptoms, live or work in a high-risk setting, are an organ donor or recipient, or are a returned traveller in quarantine.  According to the Department of Health's website (see https://web.archive.org/web/20211002095837/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/ongoing-support-during-coronavirus-covid-19/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19#how-to-get-tested), despite the national testing policy, state and territory health authorities may modify testing criteria according to local needs.
column90: Contact tracing for COVID-19 is the responsibility of state and territory governments. The Australian Government has developed the COVIDSafe app, which uses Bluetooth to detect potential contacts and assist state and territory health departments with manual contact tracing. Using the COVIDSafe app is voluntary. See https://web.archive.org/web/20210626000319/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/apps-and-tools/covidsafe-app
column103: As of 7 October 2021, masking advice and mandates are the responsibility of local, state and territory governments, and there is no nationwide mask policy. This is a continuation of conditions in place since at least 18 March 2021. column106: As of 1 October 2021, everyone aged 12 years and older is eligible for COVID-19 vaccination. Australia uses the AstraZeneca, Moderna, and Pfizer vaccines; Moderna and Pfizer are available for those 12 years and older, while AstraZeneca is available for those aged 60 years and older, or anyone 18 years and older after consulting with a health professional. This is a continuation of previous policy. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211002074342/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated.
column115: Management of COVID-19 risks to aged care is ultimately the responsibility of state and territory governments; however, the Australian Government outlines national guidelines in its National COVID-19 Aged Care Plan. Measures recommended by the plan include:  -	Use of PPE  -	Infection control training for staff  -	Screening staff and visitors for symptoms or exposure risks  -	Testing of residents and staff  -	Vaccination of residents and staff  See https://web.archive.org/web/20210403151253/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/collections/national-covid-19-aged-care-plan, https://web.archive.org/web/20211126155155/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2021/03/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia_0.pdf.

The payment was $200 per week for those who are already receiving income support and lose at least 8 hours a week, $450 per week for those not already receiving income support and lose 8-20 hours a week, and $750 per week for those not already receiving income support who lose 20 or more hours per week. The Government began phasing out the COVID-19 Disaster Payment when states and territories reached 70% full vaccination rate among the 16+ population. column77: The Australian Government continues to provide income support to formal workers - the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment - to households who cannot work due to quarantine, self-isolation, or caring for someone with COVID-19. There is also a COVID-19 Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for workers unable to earn an income due to state or territory public health orders (e.g. a lockdown). The payment was $200 per week for those who are already receiving income support and lose at least 8 hours a week, $450 per week for those not already receiving income support and lose 8-20 hours a week, and $750 per week for those not already receiving income support who lose 20 or more hours per week. The maximum payment amount of $750 per week is more than half the median income, which is $1209 per week. The Government began phasing out the COVID-19 Disaster Payment when states and territories reached 70% full vaccination rate among the 16+ population. (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - ban arrivals from some regions - 3    People must show evidence that they have been vaccinated, at least 7 days prior to international travel into or out of Australia, with a vaccine approved or recognised by the Therapeutic Goods Administration (TGA). Non-Australian travellers need an exemption to come into Australia even if they are vaccinated with a recognised vaccine.    Additionally, the Australian Government has announced new border security measures to protect Australians from the Omicron COVID-19 variant. Effective immediately, on 27/November/2021, anyone who is not a citizen or permanent resident of Australia, or their immediate family including parents of citizens, and who have been in African countries where the Omicron variant has been detected and spread  within the past 14 days  will not be able to enter Australia. The countries are: South Africa, Namibia, Zimbabwe, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini, Seychelles, Malawi and Mozambique. The Government will suspend all flights from the nine southern African countries for a period of 14 days as a matter of precaution.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211209050429/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20211209023645/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20211214154047/https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/additional-border-security-measures-to-protect-australians-from-the-new-omicron-covid-19-variant

column15: According to the statement released by AHPPC on 15 November 2021 schools should remain open whenever possible. They have introduced three principles that schools need to follow in order to minimize transmission when schools are open.   "Each of these principles has actions that should be considered when planning re-opening of schools noting that multiple steps will need to be taken and that these will need to be tailored by individual schools to be most effective.  Measures that are implemented should be evaluated for effect, cost-effectiveness, feasibility, sustainability and adverse consequences."     The states and territories are responsible for determining the appropriate response in the event of a community outbreak. Thus, there is no national policy with regard to school closing.     https://web.archive.org/web/20211201015930/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-statement-on-covid-19-schools-and-early-childhood-education-and-care

column86: There are a variety of campaigns coordinated by the Australian Government across traditional and social media.    For example, on 24 Oct 2021, the Australian Government has launched a new phase of the COVID-19 advertising campaign (Spread Freedom) to encourage eligible Australians continue to come forward to be vaccinated against COVID-19. The campaign will be rolled out across a range of channels, including television, radio, print, digital and social media. Materials will also be adapted for culturally and linguistically diverse audiences.    On 17 Dec 2021, the Australian Government has launched the latest phase of the COVID-19 campaign (COVID-19 booster vaccinations) to encourage eligible Australians to book their booster vaccination as soon as they are eligible. The campaign will be rolled out across a range of channels, including television, radio, print, digital and social media.    The policy is in place in the entire country. column103: According to AHPPC statement on the Omicron public health implications and response options published on 22 Dec 2021, the AHPPC has agreed a recommendation for wearing of facemasks in indoor settings, noting that this is a particularly important in high risk settings. Face masks have a minimal impact on individuals and the economy, provide confidence to the community, and have shown to be beneficial in reducing transmission of disease. Masks should be mandated in all indoor settings including retail, hospitality when not eating or drinking, and entertainment facilities. Implementation of mask wearing measures should occur prior to Omicron case escalation to have maximum benefit.    This policy is in place in the entire country.    Therefore, it should be reported as 1G.    Archived link: https://archive.ph/zdNKF
